#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:10
msgid "Differences from `!psycopg2`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:12
msgid ""
"Psycopg 3 uses the common DBAPI structure of many other database adapters "
"and tries to behave as close as possible to `!psycopg2`. There are however a "
"few differences to be aware of."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:17
msgid ""
"Most of the times, the workarounds suggested here will work with both "
"Psycopg 2 and 3, which could be useful if you are porting a program or "
"writing a program that should work with both Psycopg 2 and 3."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:25
msgid "Which package to install?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:29
msgid ""
"If you were installing ``psycopg2-binary`` you should now install "
"``psycopg[binary]`` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:32
msgid ""
"If you were installing ``psycopg2``, therefore your client has the "
"prerequisites to build the C extension yourself, you can install "
"``psycopg[c]`` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:36
msgid ""
"Please see the :ref:`installation <installation>` section for all the "
"details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:38
msgid ""
"Rationale: both the ``psycopg2`` and the ``psycopg2-binary`` distribution "
"packages install the ``psycopg2`` Python package. This scenario is not well "
"covered by Python packaging metadata, resulting in complex dependencies "
"management and problems if both the packages are installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:43
msgid ""
"In Psycopg 3 there is a clear \"interface\" package, ``psycopg``, and "
"optional speed-up extensions that can be included in the dependencies of a "
"service (but don't need to -- and shouldn't be -- included in the "
"dependencies of a library). See :ref:`install-dependencies` for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:52
msgid "Server-side binding"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:54
msgid ""
"Psycopg 3 sends the query and the parameters to the server separately, "
"instead of merging them on the client side. Server-side binding works for "
"normal :sql:`SELECT` and data manipulation statements (:sql:`INSERT`, :sql:"
"`UPDATE`, :sql:`DELETE`), but it doesn't work with many other statements. "
"For instance, it doesn't work with :sql:`SET` or with :sql:`NOTIFY`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:60
msgid ""
">>> conn.execute(\"SET TimeZone TO %s\", [\"UTC\"])\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"...\n"
"psycopg.errors.SyntaxError: syntax error at or near \"$1\"\n"
"LINE 1: SET TimeZone TO $1\n"
"                        ^\n"
"\n"
">>> conn.execute(\"NOTIFY %s, %s\", [\"chan\", 42])\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"...\n"
"psycopg.errors.SyntaxError: syntax error at or near \"$1\"\n"
"LINE 1: NOTIFY $1, $2\n"
"               ^"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:74
msgid "and with any data definition statement::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:76
msgid ""
">>> conn.execute(\"CREATE TABLE foo (id int DEFAULT %s)\", [42])\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"...\n"
"psycopg.errors.UndefinedParameter: there is no parameter $1\n"
"LINE 1: CREATE TABLE foo (id int DEFAULT $1)\n"
"                                         ^"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:83
msgid ""
"Sometimes, PostgreSQL offers an alternative: for instance the "
"`set_config()`__ function can be used instead of the :sql:`SET` statement, "
"the `pg_notify()`__ function can be used instead of :sql:`NOTIFY`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:87
msgid ""
">>> conn.execute(\"SELECT set_config('TimeZone', %s, false)\", [\"UTC\"])\n"
"\n"
">>> conn.execute(\"SELECT pg_notify(%s, %s)\", [\"chan\", \"42\"])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:97
msgid ""
"If this is not possible, you must merge the query and the parameter on the "
"client side. You can do so using the `psycopg.sql` objects::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:100
msgid ""
">>> from psycopg import sql\n"
"\n"
">>> cur.execute(sql.SQL(\"CREATE TABLE foo (id int DEFAULT {})\").format(42))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:104
msgid ""
"or creating a :ref:`client-side binding cursor <client-side-binding-"
"cursors>` such as `ClientCursor`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:107
msgid ""
">>> cur = ClientCursor(conn)\n"
">>> cur.execute(\"CREATE TABLE foo (id int DEFAULT %s)\", [42])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:110
msgid ""
"If you need `!ClientCursor` often, you can set the `Connection."
"cursor_factory` to have them created by default by `Connection.cursor()`. "
"This way, Psycopg 3 will behave largely the same way of Psycopg 2."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:114
msgid ""
"Note that, both server-side and client-side, you can only specify **values** "
"as parameters (i.e. *the strings that go in single quotes*). If you need to "
"parametrize different parts of a statement (such as a table name), you must "
"use the `psycopg.sql` module::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:119
msgid ""
">>> from psycopg import sql\n"
"\n"
"# This will quote the user and the password using the right quotes\n"
"# e.g.: ALTER USER \"foo\" SET PASSWORD 'bar'\n"
">>> conn.execute(\n"
"...     sql.SQL(\"ALTER USER {} SET PASSWORD {}\")\n"
"...     .format(sql.Identifier(username), password))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:135
msgid "Extended query Protocol"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:137
msgid ""
"In order to use :ref:`server-side-binding`, psycopg normally uses the "
"`extended query protocol`__ to communicate with the backend."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:140
msgid ""
"In certain context outside pure PostgreSQL, the extended query protocol is "
"not supported, for instance to query the `PgBouncer admin console`__. In "
"this case you should probably use a `ClientCursor`. See :ref:`simple-query-"
"protocol` for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:152
msgid "Multiple statements in the same query"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:154
msgid ""
"As a consequence of using :ref:`server-side bindings <server-side-binding>`, "
"when parameters are used, it is not possible to execute several statements "
"in the same `!execute()` call, separating them by semicolon::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:158
msgid ""
">>> conn.execute(\n"
"...     \"INSERT INTO foo VALUES (%s); INSERT INTO foo VALUES (%s)\",\n"
"...     (10, 20))\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"...\n"
"psycopg.errors.SyntaxError: cannot insert multiple commands into a prepared "
"statement"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:165
msgid ""
"One obvious way to work around the problem is to use several `!execute()` "
"calls."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:168
msgid ""
"**There is no such limitation if no parameters are used**. As a consequence, "
"you can compose a multiple query on the client side and run them all in the "
"same `!execute()` call, using the `psycopg.sql` objects::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:172
msgid ""
">>> from psycopg import sql\n"
">>> conn.execute(\n"
"...     sql.SQL(\"INSERT INTO foo VALUES ({}); INSERT INTO foo values "
"({})\")\n"
"...     .format(10, 20))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:177
msgid "or a :ref:`client-side binding cursor <client-side-binding-cursors>`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:179
msgid ""
">>> cur = psycopg.ClientCursor(conn)\n"
">>> cur.execute(\n"
"...     \"INSERT INTO foo VALUES (%s); INSERT INTO foo VALUES (%s)\",\n"
"...     (10, 20))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:186
msgid "You cannot execute multiple statements in the same query:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:188
msgid ""
"when retrieving a :ref:`binary result <binary-data>` (such as using ``."
"execute(..., binary=True)``;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:190
msgid "when using the :ref:`pipeline mode <pipeline-mode>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:194
msgid ""
"If a statement must be executed outside a transaction (such as :sql:`CREATE "
"DATABASE`), it cannot be executed in batch with other statements, even if "
"the connection is in autocommit mode::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:198
msgid ""
">>> conn.autocommit = True\n"
">>> conn.execute(\"CREATE DATABASE foo; SELECT 1\")\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"...\n"
"psycopg.errors.ActiveSqlTransaction: CREATE DATABASE cannot run inside a "
"transaction block"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:204
msgid ""
"This happens because PostgreSQL itself will wrap multiple statements in a "
"transaction. Note that you will experience a different behaviour in :program:"
"`psql` (:program:`psql` will split the queries on semicolons and send them "
"to the server separately)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:209
msgid ""
"This is not new in Psycopg 3: the same limitation is present in `!psycopg2` "
"too."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:216
msgid "Multiple results returned from multiple statements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:218
msgid ""
"If more than one statement returning results is executed in psycopg2, only "
"the result of the last statement is returned::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:221
msgid ""
">>> cur_pg2.execute(\"SELECT 1; SELECT 2\")\n"
">>> cur_pg2.fetchone()\n"
"(2,)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:225
msgid ""
"In Psycopg 3 instead, all the results are available. After running the "
"query, the first result will be readily available in the cursor and can be "
"consumed using the usual `!fetch*()` methods. In order to access the "
"following results, you can use the `Cursor.results()` method (or `~Cursor."
"nextset()` before Psycopg 3.3)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:231
msgid ""
">>> cur_pg3.execute(\"SELECT 1; SELECT 2\")\n"
">>> for _ in cur_pg3.results():\n"
"...    print(cur_pg3.fetchone())\n"
"(1,)\n"
"(2,)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:237
msgid ""
"Remember though that you cannot use server-side bindings to :ref:`execute "
"more than one statement in the same query <multi-statements>`, if you are "
"passing parameters to the query."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:245
msgid "Different cast rules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:247
msgid ""
"In rare cases, especially around variadic functions, PostgreSQL might fail "
"to find a function candidate for the given data types::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:250
msgid ""
">>> conn.execute(\"SELECT json_build_array(%s, %s)\", [\"foo\", \"bar\"])\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"...\n"
"psycopg.errors.IndeterminateDatatype: could not determine data type of "
"parameter $1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:255
msgid ""
"This can be worked around specifying the argument types explicitly via a "
"cast::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:257
msgid ""
">>> conn.execute(\"SELECT json_build_array(%s::text, %s::text)\", [\"foo\", "
"\"bar\"])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:263
msgid "You cannot use ``IN %s`` with a tuple"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:265
msgid ""
"``IN`` cannot be used with a tuple as single parameter, as was possible with "
"``psycopg2``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:268
msgid ""
">>> conn.execute(\"SELECT * FROM foo WHERE id IN %s\", [(10,20,30)])\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"...\n"
"psycopg.errors.SyntaxError: syntax error at or near \"$1\"\n"
"LINE 1: SELECT * FROM foo WHERE id IN $1\n"
"                                      ^"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:275
msgid ""
"What you can do is to use the `= ANY()`__ construct and pass the candidate "
"values as a list instead of a tuple, which will be adapted to a PostgreSQL "
"array::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:279
msgid ""
">>> conn.execute(\"SELECT * FROM foo WHERE id = ANY(%s)\", [[10,20,30]])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:281
msgid ""
"Note that `ANY()` can be used with `!psycopg2` too, and has the advantage of "
"accepting an empty list of values too as argument, which is not supported by "
"the :sql:`IN` operator instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:292
msgid "You cannot use ``IS %s``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:294
msgid "You cannot use :sql:`IS %s` or :sql:`IS NOT %s`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:296
msgid ""
">>> conn.execute(\"SELECT * FROM foo WHERE field IS %s\", [None])\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"...\n"
"psycopg.errors.SyntaxError: syntax error at or near \"$1\"\n"
"LINE 1: SELECT * FROM foo WHERE field IS $1\n"
"                                     ^"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:303
msgid ""
"This is probably caused by the fact that :sql:`IS` is not a binary predicate "
"in PostgreSQL; rather, :sql:`IS NULL` and :sql:`IS NOT NULL` are unary "
"predicates and you cannot use :sql:`IS` with anything else on the right hand "
"side. Testing in psql:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:308
msgid ""
"=# SELECT 10 IS 10;\n"
"ERROR:  syntax error at or near \"10\"\n"
"LINE 1: SELECT 10 IS 10;\n"
"                     ^"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:315
msgid ""
"What you can do is to use `IS [NOT] DISTINCT FROM`__ predicate instead: :sql:"
"`IS NOT DISTINCT FROM %s` can be used in place of :sql:`IS %s` (please pay "
"attention to the awkwardly reversed :sql:`NOT`)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:319
msgid ""
">>> conn.execute(\"SELECT * FROM foo WHERE field IS NOT DISTINCT FROM %s\", "
"[None])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:323
msgid ""
"Analogously you can use :sql:`IS DISTINCT FROM %s` as a parametric version "
"of :sql:`IS NOT %s`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:330
msgid "Cursors subclasses"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:332
msgid ""
"In `!psycopg2`, a few cursor subclasses allowed to return data in different "
"form than tuples. In Psycopg 3 the same can be achieved by setting a :ref:"
"`row factory <row-factories>`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:336
msgid ""
"instead of `~psycopg2.extras.RealDictCursor` you can use `~psycopg.rows."
"dict_row`;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:339
msgid ""
"instead of `~psycopg2.extras.NamedTupleCursor` you can use `~psycopg.rows."
"namedtuple_row`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:342
msgid ""
"Other row factories are available in the `psycopg.rows` module. There isn't "
"an object behaving like `~psycopg2.extras.DictCursor` (whose results are "
"indexable both by column position and by column name)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:346
msgid ""
"from psycopg.rows import dict_row, namedtuple_row\n"
"\n"
"# By default, every cursor will return dicts.\n"
"conn = psycopg.connect(DSN, row_factory=dict_row)\n"
"\n"
"# You can set a row factory on a single cursor too.\n"
"cur = conn.cursor(row_factory=namedtuple_row)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:360
msgid "Different adaptation system"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:362
msgid ""
"The adaptation system has been completely rewritten, in order to address "
"server-side parameters adaptation, but also to consider performance, "
"flexibility, ease of customization."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:366
msgid ""
"The default behaviour with builtin data should be :ref:`what you would "
"expect <types-adaptation>`. If you have customised the way to adapt data, or "
"if you are managing your own extension types, you should look at the :ref:"
"`new adaptation system <adaptation>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:373
msgid ":ref:`types-adaptation` for the basic behaviour."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:374
msgid ":ref:`adaptation` for more advanced use."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:380
msgid "Copy is no longer file-based"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:382
msgid ""
"`!psycopg2` exposes :ref:`a few copy methods <pg2:copy>` to interact with "
"PostgreSQL :sql:`COPY`. Their file-based interface doesn't make it easy to "
"load dynamically-generated data into a database."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:386
msgid ""
"There is now a single `~Cursor.copy()` method, which is similar to `!"
"psycopg2` `!copy_expert()` in accepting a free-form :sql:`COPY` command and "
"returns an object to read/write data, block-wise or record-wise. The "
"different usage pattern also enables :sql:`COPY` to be used in async "
"interactions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:391
msgid "See :ref:`copy` for the details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:397
msgid "`!with` connection"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:399
msgid ""
"In `!psycopg2`, using the syntax :ref:`with connection <pg2:with>`, only the "
"transaction is closed, not the connection. This behaviour is surprising for "
"people used to several other Python classes wrapping resources, such as "
"files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:404
msgid ""
"In Psycopg 3, using :ref:`with connection <with-connection>` will close the "
"connection at the end of the `!with` block, making handling the connection "
"resources more familiar."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:408
msgid ""
"In order to manage transactions as blocks you can use the `Connection."
"transaction()` method, which allows for finer control, for instance to use "
"nested transactions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:412
msgid "See :ref:`transaction-context` for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:418
msgid "`!callproc()` is gone"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:420
msgid ""
"`cursor.callproc()` is not implemented. The method has a simplistic semantic "
"which doesn't account for PostgreSQL positional parameters, procedures, set-"
"returning functions... Use a normal `~Cursor.execute()` with :sql:`SELECT "
"function_name(...)` or :sql:`CALL procedure_name(...)` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:429
msgid "`!client_encoding` is gone"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:431
msgid ""
"Psycopg automatically uses the database client encoding to decode data to "
"Unicode strings. Use `ConnectionInfo.encoding` if you need to read the "
"encoding. You can select an encoding at connection time using the `!"
"client_encoding` connection parameter and you can change the encoding of a "
"connection by running a :sql:`SET client_encoding` statement... But why "
"would you?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:442
msgid "Transaction characteristics attributes don't affect autocommit sessions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:444
msgid ""
":ref:`Transactions characteristics attributes <transaction-characteristics>` "
"such as `~Connection.read_only` don't affect automatically autocommit "
"sessions: they only affect the implicit transactions started by non-"
"autocommit sessions and the transactions created by the `~Connection."
"transaction()` block (for both autocommit and non-autocommit connections)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:450
msgid ""
"If you want to put an autocommit transaction in read-only mode, please use "
"the default_transaction_read_only__ GUC, for instance executing the "
"statement :sql:`SET default_transaction_read_only TO true`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:461
msgid "No default infinity dates handling"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:463
msgid ""
"PostgreSQL can represent a much wider range of dates and timestamps than "
"Python. While Python dates are limited to the years between 1 and 9999 "
"(represented by constants such as `datetime.date.min` and `~datetime.date."
"max`), PostgreSQL dates extend to BC dates and past the year 10K. "
"Furthermore PostgreSQL can also represent symbolic dates \"infinity\", in "
"both directions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:470
msgid ""
"In psycopg2, by default, `infinity dates and timestamps map to 'date.max'`__ "
"and similar constants. This has the problem of creating a non-bijective "
"mapping (two Postgres dates, infinity and 9999-12-31, both map to the same "
"Python date). There is also the perversity that valid Postgres dates, "
"greater than Python `!date.max` but arguably lesser than infinity, will "
"still overflow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/from_pg2.rst:477
msgid ""
"In Psycopg 3, every date greater than year 9999 will overflow, including "
"infinity. If you would like to customize this mapping (for instance "
"flattening every date past Y10K on `!date.max`) you can subclass and adapt "
"the appropriate loaders: take a look at :ref:`this example <adapt-example-"
"inf-date>` to see how."
msgstr ""

